WEBVTT

00:08.074 --> 00:09.576
Hey, Frasier.

00:09.576 --> 00:10.577
Hello, Poppy.

00:10.577 --> 00:12.078
You should have your
hearing checked.

00:12.078 --> 00:13.079
I've been yelling,
"Wait up,"

00:13.079 --> 00:14.381
for the last
four blocks.

00:14.381 --> 00:15.648
Well, I must be getting old.

00:15.648 --> 00:17.650
Like an old man
could walk that fast.

00:18.151 --> 00:19.152
You were practically running
the last block.

00:19.152 --> 00:21.154
Did I ever tell you about
my uncle who ran everywhere?

00:21.154 --> 00:22.088
He ran to the store...

00:22.088 --> 00:24.024
Well, that's
a very amusing story.

00:24.024 --> 00:24.824
I'll see you
at the station.

00:24.824 --> 00:26.559
Roz!

00:26.559 --> 00:28.962
Good God. Thank
God you were here.

00:28.962 --> 00:30.463
I know exactly how
you feel.

00:30.463 --> 00:31.898
Last week, I ducked
into a bathroom stall

00:31.898 --> 00:32.966
to get away from her,
and there were

00:32.966 --> 00:34.801
three other women
already in there.

00:35.635 --> 00:37.637
Gosh.

00:37.637 --> 00:38.538
Listen, I have
a favor to ask.

00:38.538 --> 00:39.372
This friend of mine
is running

00:39.372 --> 00:40.940
this charity dinner/dance
Friday night...

00:40.940 --> 00:42.208
Oh, Roz,
say no more.

00:42.208 --> 00:43.476
What do they need,
an autographed picture

00:43.476 --> 00:44.344
for their silent auction?

00:44.344 --> 00:46.646
That would be a silent auction.

00:46.646 --> 00:47.981
Oh, very funny.

00:47.981 --> 00:49.449
No, what I was hoping you would
do is buy some tickets.

00:49.449 --> 00:51.384
They're only 100 bucks each.

00:51.384 --> 00:52.352
I don't know, Roz.

00:52.352 --> 00:53.319
You know,
I'd have to take a date.

00:53.319 --> 00:54.821
Seattle does have
certain expectations

00:54.821 --> 00:56.790
about the sort of person
I should be seen with.

00:56.790 --> 00:58.591
Well, that's easy.
Here he is. Oh.

00:58.591 --> 01:00.326
Let's see if he's free.
I'll let you know.

01:00.326 --> 01:02.729
Hey, Roz. Frasier.

01:02.729 --> 01:03.730
Niles.
Mind if I join you?

01:03.730 --> 01:05.230
Well, actually,
I'm not staying.

01:05.230 --> 01:06.299
I'm avoiding
someone.

01:06.299 --> 01:08.301
Oh? Who?

01:08.301 --> 01:09.736
The new so-called
arts critic

01:09.736 --> 01:12.072
at the station--
Poppy. Oh. Uh-huh.

01:12.072 --> 01:13.273
The woman
drives me mad.

01:13.273 --> 01:14.841
She's gassing
on endlessly

01:14.841 --> 01:16.176
about the most
mundane matters.

01:16.176 --> 01:18.011
It's absolutely
infuriating,

01:18.011 --> 01:20.380
as is that
smirk of yours.

01:20.380 --> 01:21.681
Well, I'm sorry.

01:21.681 --> 01:23.249
I've noticed
that not a day goes by

01:23.249 --> 01:25.085
that you don't bad-mouth
this woman.

01:25.085 --> 01:27.921
Well, with good reason.
The woman is a wind sock.

01:27.921 --> 01:28.755
Mm-hmm.

01:28.755 --> 01:29.589
I'm wondering
if someone

01:29.589 --> 01:31.591
isn't protesting
a bit too much.

01:31.591 --> 01:34.594
She's very attractive,
obviously well-bred.

01:34.594 --> 01:37.063
Perhaps all this pigtails-
in-the-inkwell hostility

01:37.063 --> 01:39.065
is actually a latent attraction.

01:39.065 --> 01:40.533
Oh, well, bravo,
Dr. Crane.

01:40.533 --> 01:42.402
Yes, I think you're really
onto something there.

01:42.402 --> 01:44.070
POPPY:
Hey, where'd Roz go?

01:44.070 --> 01:45.338
Oh, she dashed
off to the office.

01:45.338 --> 01:46.906
We're going to continue
our meeting there.

01:46.906 --> 01:48.241
You know, Poppy,
I was just telling my brother

01:48.241 --> 01:51.111
what an enchanting
storyteller you are.

01:51.111 --> 01:53.113
Why don't you
take my seat,

01:53.113 --> 01:55.615
and he can find
out for himself.

01:55.615 --> 01:57.617
Ta-ta.

01:57.617 --> 01:59.119
Well, it's, uh,

01:59.119 --> 02:01.121
nice to finally
meet you, Poppy.

02:01.621 --> 02:04.991
Must be quite a story
behind that name.

02:04.991 --> 02:06.793
Yes.

02:08.661 --> 02:11.164
So...

02:11.164 --> 02:12.665
you're the new arts critic
at the station.

02:12.665 --> 02:15.101
That... that must be
interesting.

02:15.101 --> 02:17.337
Oh, yes.

02:17.337 --> 02:20.240
Okay, well, um...

02:20.240 --> 02:21.241
if you don't feel
like talking,

02:21.241 --> 02:22.742
I should really
be running anyway.

02:22.742 --> 02:23.676
No, don't go.

02:23.676 --> 02:25.612
I am just amazed

02:25.612 --> 02:27.447
at how different you are
from your brother.

02:27.447 --> 02:29.249
He's sort of
intimidating.

02:29.249 --> 02:30.750
I get so flustered
around him,

02:30.750 --> 02:32.285
I just start
babbling.

02:32.285 --> 02:35.555
But you...
you're different.

02:35.555 --> 02:37.790
You're very warm.

02:37.790 --> 02:39.259
Thank you.

02:39.259 --> 02:41.261
So are you.

02:41.261 --> 02:42.762
And polite.

02:42.762 --> 02:45.698
Not to mention
stylish and charming

02:45.698 --> 02:49.002
and incredibly handsome.

02:50.737 --> 02:53.506
Oh, my God, am
I babbling again?

02:53.506 --> 02:54.941
If you were,
I'd be too charming

02:54.941 --> 02:56.409
and polite to tell you.

03:01.314 --> 03:05.652
Well, what the
hell are you doing?

03:08.588 --> 03:10.423
I've been waiting

03:10.423 --> 03:12.292
for 20 minutes.

03:13.293 --> 03:15.762
I am so sorry.

03:15.762 --> 03:18.031
You're probably
wondering

03:18.031 --> 03:19.732
who I am.

03:19.732 --> 03:22.669
I'm mildly curious.

03:22.669 --> 03:25.638
I was in the shower--
my shower...

03:25.638 --> 03:27.640
Uh, I just moved in next door.

03:27.640 --> 03:29.642
I probably should have started
with that, huh?

03:29.642 --> 03:31.644
Anyway... oh, I'm
Regan Shaw, by the way.

03:31.644 --> 03:33.413
Nice to see you.
Anyway, uh...

03:33.413 --> 03:35.615
the doorbell rang, and I figured
it was the phone guy,

03:35.615 --> 03:37.183
'cause I've been waiting
all day long.

03:37.183 --> 03:40.186
So I ran to catch him,
stepped out into the hallway

03:40.186 --> 03:41.955
and locked myself out.

03:41.955 --> 03:46.259
Luckily, luckily,
your father came along.

03:47.260 --> 03:49.062
Hey, Fras.

03:49.062 --> 03:51.231
Yes, that was lucky.

03:51.231 --> 03:53.066
All right, well, this
should keep you nice and warm,

03:53.066 --> 03:54.567
and I'll just run
in the kitchen

03:54.567 --> 03:57.303
and get you
your herbal tea.

03:57.303 --> 03:59.138
If you'll excuse me,

03:59.138 --> 04:01.107
I'll just show my father

04:01.107 --> 04:03.009
where it's kept.

04:03.810 --> 04:05.845
Pretty sweet, huh?

04:05.845 --> 04:06.846
I just found her
right out in the hall.

04:06.846 --> 04:09.282
Yes, well, I'm sorry, Dad,
but you can't keep her.

04:11.618 --> 04:13.620
No. I brought her here for you.

04:13.620 --> 04:16.089
I've been talking you up
the whole time. Really?

04:16.089 --> 04:17.490
Yeah. Listen.

04:17.490 --> 04:19.791
I'm serving this one
to you on a platter.

04:19.791 --> 04:22.562
In fact, if it wasn't
for the jasmine on your robe,

04:22.562 --> 04:24.364
I'd say that this one
was a slam dunk.

04:24.364 --> 04:25.565
I just wonder...
It's a basketball term.

04:25.565 --> 04:27.567
Yes, I know that, Dad.

04:27.567 --> 04:30.003
I just wonder how to chat up
a half-naked woman

04:30.503 --> 04:31.804
without looking uncouth.

04:31.804 --> 04:33.640
Well, just
be friendly.

04:33.640 --> 04:36.476
She's a veterinarian,
she's single, uh...

04:36.476 --> 04:39.312
She's very athletic,
as you can tell from that body.

04:39.312 --> 04:40.680
Lord in heaven!

04:40.680 --> 04:42.015
Oh, Dad, please...

04:42.015 --> 04:43.516
Just because you're
serving the cake

04:43.516 --> 04:44.984
doesn't mean you can't
have a few crumbs

04:44.984 --> 04:47.387
that drop off.
(groans)

04:47.387 --> 04:48.788
(chuckling):
Hi.

04:48.788 --> 04:51.791
Well, here we go.

04:51.791 --> 04:52.625
There you are.

04:52.625 --> 04:54.494
Now, uh, I got
a call to make,

04:54.494 --> 04:56.996
so Frasier will keep you
entertained.

04:56.996 --> 04:57.997
Thanks for the tea.

04:57.997 --> 04:59.432
You're welcome.

04:59.432 --> 05:02.802
So, uh... you're next door.

05:02.802 --> 05:04.570
Oh, that's right.

05:04.570 --> 05:07.740
Judge Gilroy moved
in with his daughter.

05:07.740 --> 05:10.443
I bet he never wandered into
your apartment wearing a towel.

05:10.443 --> 05:11.811
No, no. I did
hear he wandered

05:11.811 --> 05:14.314
into work one day
wearing a towel, though.

05:14.314 --> 05:16.816
I guess that's why he had
to move in with his daughter.

05:16.816 --> 05:19.686
That was dumb.
I walked off with your car keys.

05:19.686 --> 05:22.889
I should have known
from the big "BMW" on it.

05:28.261 --> 05:31.197
Thank you, Dad.

05:31.197 --> 05:33.032
So...

05:33.032 --> 05:35.401
"Regan." That's an unusual name.

05:35.401 --> 05:36.869
Is it, by any chance, from...

05:36.869 --> 05:37.837
From King Lear, yeah.
A-ha.

05:37.837 --> 05:39.672
One of the ungrateful
daughters.

05:39.672 --> 05:41.841
I don't know what
my dad was thinking.

05:41.841 --> 05:43.643
Never do.

05:43.643 --> 05:45.144
I'm sorry.

05:45.144 --> 05:47.447
I have some issues
with my father.

05:47.447 --> 05:49.248
Excuse me again.

05:50.249 --> 05:53.586
I have no idea what
that would be like.

05:57.290 --> 05:58.691
Well, I'd better be
on my way, huh,

05:58.691 --> 06:00.360
and, uh,

06:00.360 --> 06:01.994
just let you
two talk.

06:01.994 --> 06:04.364
Oh, he's a wonderful
listener, you know?

06:04.364 --> 06:05.865
In fact, that's the motto

06:05.865 --> 06:08.801
on his very popular
radio show: "I listen."

06:08.801 --> 06:10.670
Yes, Dad,
don't forget

06:10.670 --> 06:12.805
my sign-off:
"Good-bye."

06:17.877 --> 06:19.812
I actually listen to your show.

06:19.812 --> 06:22.281
Really? Well, I'm
flattered. Thank you.

06:22.281 --> 06:24.217
I think if I hadn't gone
into veterinary medicine,

06:24.217 --> 06:25.485
it would have been psychology.

06:25.485 --> 06:29.255
I guess I was always
just drawn to animals.

06:31.724 --> 06:34.727
Yes, it is hard
not to love them.

